>>54709937
At first, jubilation. The Fermi Paradox and the Great Filter are no more. Our species will likely survive. The universe is not barren
Then, abject horror. Any species that can travel between planets has ecliped us technologically. Not like muskets to machineguns, but more like stone clubs to fission warheads. If they are hostile, we are completely at their mercy.
Third, oportunism. Every government on Earth will be scrambling to aquire any scrap of alien tech they can get their hands on. They will all be desperate to level the playing field as soon as possible. Any nation that incorporates alien tech into their economies will quickly outpace everyone else.
Fourth, appeasement. Given that no human nation could stand up to the arrivals, everyone will compete for their favor. If the arrivals are hostile, it will be for better terms of surrender. If the arrivals are benevolet, it will be for first dibs on whatever they're handing out. After all, if you don't take it, your belligerent neighbor with dreams of empire will, and who knows what he'll do with all that fancy tech. That petty third-world dictator will abosultely sell out his nation for fancy hovertanks, so you better get them first. Everyone will be competing for the alien's favor.

And throughout all of this, people will want to fuck them.

Anonymous Mon 27 Feb 2023 05:55:08 No.54711320 Report

>>54710712
anything where you say "I'll figure that out later", that's not what I'm talking about.
Nor is it years of prep work and outlining. You're not writing a historical novel or hard sci-fi that has more detail than a doctoral thesis.

Let's take HATSSSSS as an example.
If kaktus has a plan (that works for him), he has answers to the big-ticket questions surrounding Missy. This is the difference between something that is slow but plotted and something that is just a "I wanted to" story. You rarely have all the answers, but understanding the shape of them is a minimum.
Do you have an ending in mind?
Can you define the main characters' conflicts/motivations?
Do you have a rough outline, even if it's just one sentence per scene and with plenty of blank areas, that lets you work on later parts if you get writer's block on earlier bits?

Basically, it's finding a level of prep that lets you fill in what you don't know as you write the first draft. Could be you write the entire story and do two to four drafts, or you do a chapter at a time. But you're never at a complete loss. If you can ask questions, then there was some level of planning before that.

Oh, and the most important part is discipline. No one writes without an ounce of inspiration, but if you need inspiration for even the smallest writing tasks, a measure of planning/discipline will let you pants way better.

And with that, I've been way too wordy and pretentious.

The tech difference does seem likely, but then again, I have seen a couple of authors make less of a mismatch look plausible for story purposes. There's a short story from the 1980s by Harry Turtledove called "The Road Not Taken," in which mid-21st-Century Earth gets a visit from aliens bent on conquest. They set down their enormous antigravity starships in places like public parks in major cities all over the world, then the aliens, kind of resembling anthro koala bears, climb out and form ranks with muzzleloading muskets and fire into the crowds of onlookers. What follows is not so much a war as a curbstomp that goes on for about an afternoon. The handful of shellshocked, mindboggled survivors are interviewed, once linguists learn their language, and don't understand what the fuck happened. It turns out that a very simple arrangement of magnets and quartz crystals and other really mundane shit creates antigravity and an only slightly more complex one is an FTL stardrive. Humans just never stumbled across it. The aliens did, and all their technological development halted a couple thousand years back because they immediately started up an interstellar empire and began looting every other civilization they could find, stealing ships full of grain, and slave laborers. It turned out there are lots of other sophont species out there, and the relative plenty made this particular bunch a lot less curious about how stuff actually worked and technological development halted at the matchlock arquebus. Not many of them stumble across antigravity and the stardrive. Very few ever develop past the Bronze Age. Humans didn't get the stardrive. Instead we got knowledge of the universe, atomic bombs and TV and genetic engineering. Later stories say that humans also dropped everything else for interstellar exploration. One character prepares to fight off space pirates with a family heirloom AK47 four hundred years old, because there's nothing much better anyway.

I think the main marker of a "real" Trek series is whether or not it exists in the continuity of the tradition. Specifically, with people working on it in a meaningful capacity who have worked on previous Trek. That link is present from TOS to ENT, though it was clearly waning by the time ENT rolled around. You also see it in the way they made the series, with actors having a fairly big say in their characters and being recruited to direct episodes. And TOS obviously allowed spec scripts.

Anything outside of that continuity of spirit is essentially fan fiction. Or, in the case of much on NuTrek, just fiction. The Orville at least seems to try and recreate something like that continuity with heavily sourcing people who have worked on Trek.

For some languages it's difficult to get a proper feel. Russian, for example, lacks a present-tense linking verb, and article adjectives. If you go word by word it can have a Tonto/Tarzan/Frankenstein feel, though some circumlocutions are needed because of its thorny profusion of noun cases, which are suffixes that indicate one thing's relationship to others. Now imagine an alien language. It might be easiest to handwave it away and not go too deeply down the language rabbit hole.
